<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Consultation response</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chartered Institute of Housing</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Chartered Institute of Housing (CIH) is the independent voice for housing and the home of professional standards. Our goal is simple – to provide housing professionals with the advice, support and knowledge they need to be brilliant. CIH is a registere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d charity and not-for-profit organisation. This means that the money we make is put back into the organisation and funds the activities we carry out to support the housing sector. We have a diverse and growing membership of more than 22,000 people who work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in both the public and private sectors, in 20 countries on five continents across the world. Further information is available at: </span><a href="http://www.cih.org/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.cih.org</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We welcome </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Select Committee’s inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">into the effects of recent reforms to welfare support with housing costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. There have been many reforms, and the scale and speed of their implementation has heightened their impact on households, landlords, and a range of statutory and voluntary agencies. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o date, the arguments for and against these reforms have focused largely on the moral case and projected effects. As time passes it is becoming possible to assess the actual effects, and it is essential that these are understood and used to inform both deb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ate and future welfare policy.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CIH’s response covers:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Benefit cap </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Social sector size criteria </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Payment of housing benefit /universal credit to the tenant </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DWP policy development on universal credit </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local housing allowance reforms </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Localised council tax support </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our priority in this submission has been to present new information about the impact of the reforms. We have not restated analysis or concerns previously presented in our submissions, reports and media work. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our key points i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nclude:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1 in 6 tenants affected by the social sector size criteria do not have a spare room. Of the remainder, 60% have a disability of such severity that it would be unreasonable or impractical to ask them to move or pay the difference</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Current and histori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c national policy on the way social housing is used, coupled with the operation of local private housing markets, mean the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sector size criteria is causing significant and unavoidable problems for landlords and tenants</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The benefit cap is some way fro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m meeting its objectives and it will face significant barriers to meeting them in the future. Households affected by the cap are facing significant challenges, and a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">number of unintended consequences are becoming apparent</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here are still significant barrie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rs to use of options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> benefit recipients</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to manage payments to landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and these need to be properly understood and addressed where possible before direct payment can become a reality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The decision to freeze LHA rates and increase only by CPI will sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ortly mean that less than 30% of the market is available. Government’s proposal to help some areas offset this is not enough, and the intervention will become increasingly unwieldy over time</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rather than freeing local a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthorities from central g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ouncil </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has resulted in a four fold increase in Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulation across Great Britain</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The challenges of moving to direct payment of benefit to tenants are significant. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The lessons from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> six direct payment demonstration projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ful and must be used to inform the final design of the direct payment mechanism</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although universal credit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will simplify the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> structure of welfare payments</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the rules that establish entitlement to an award of benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have become more complex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recent reforms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">add to complexity,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> making the whole process much more challenging than it would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">otherwise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have been</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role played by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">good administration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> successful implementation of any new benefit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> underestimated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A failure to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">address this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will result in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> mis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">takes and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fraud leaking into the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Detailed response</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Benefit cap </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CIH worked with Haringey </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to assess the early responses to, and impacts of, the benefit cap. The effects on households, council services and local voluntary services were identified. The full report can be provided to the Committee in week commencing 14 October. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The policy is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some way from meeting its objectives, and it will face significant barriers to doing so.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The benefit income of capped households has been reduced to that of a median average working household. However, on top of this nearly all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receive help to cover 80% of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their council tax bill, and nearly 50% of affected households are receiving discretionary payments from the council. Need for these payments is likely to continue</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Only a few capped households have so far secured 16 or more hours employment. There is evide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nce that the cap is changing attitudes to work, but for many claimants there are still significant barriers to gaining employment, particularly a lack of job seeking skills, the availability and affordability of childcare, and knowledge of how to access ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ildcare </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Savings have been made to the benefit bill. However the increased expenditure on discretionary housing payments, support to help claimants deal with the effects of the cap, and homelessness are all evidence of ‘cost shunting’ between budgets at na</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tional and local level. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Households affected by the cap are facing significant challenges:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where households are facing a large shortfall, are far from the labour market, and are not receiving discretionary housing payments (DHPs), their move into serious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financial problems will be rapid</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Agencies responses can sometimes give less attention to households living in the private rented sector, who are likely to be disproportionately affected by the biggest losses and also be the peo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ple less likely to ask for he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lp</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of unintended consequences are becoming apparent:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The feared mass evictions and relocation of benefit recipients to cheaper parts of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the country has not yet materialised, but it will come because many claimants are currently relying on time-l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">imited DHPs</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some private landlords and letting agencies are withdrawing from letting to benefit recipients because of concerns over the cap and other welfare reforms. This conflicts with government policy of encouraging local authorities to place homeless </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">households in the private rented sector (PRS) and to prioritise households in employment for social housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local decision makers can learn from Haringey’s experience:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most claimants are likely to respond to the cap by seeking employment. In most</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cases c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laimants are unlikely to want or be able to relocate and will have constrained housing options if they did wish to</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many claimants are likely to need intensive and personalised support to help them respond to the cap and move into employment, so local autho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rities and other agencies need to consider the resourcing implications of this</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The introduction of universal credit may pose a further challenge to ability to support households because local authorities will no longer have data on which households are aff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ected by benefit reductions</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DHPs can be used to give claimants some ‘head room’ but will not cover all affected households and are not sustainable over the longer term. It is important to have a clear policy/strategy for targeting DHPs and this should fit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">smoothly with policy for meeting statutory homelessness obligations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The changing landscape is putting pressure on policies for homelessness, social housing allocations, housing advice, procurement of accommodation, social services’ interventions with vulne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rable households, and strategic approaches to influence future supply.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Social sector size criteria</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">still </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">early to draw </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">firm </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conclusions about the overall consequences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social sector size criteria </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for tenants and landlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but, six months in, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the early impacts are clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tenants who now face a benefit shortfall are struggling to make ends meet. If </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recently published surveys were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">replicated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK-wide,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over 330,000 tenants would be struggling to pay their rent or facing an uncertain future</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CIH rejects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the assertion that affected tenants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can choose to stay and pay the shortfall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or move to a home that more closely matches needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">happens in the PRS.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocial tenants are not as free to move as private tenants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for a number of reasons:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">housing waiting lists are not completely open, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and it has been a long standing national policy to let </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">homes largely on the basis of housing need </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he rate of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">property becoming vacant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is much slower than in the PRS. The median length of a social sector tena</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncy is seven years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the PRS it is between one and two years</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here are higher levels of disability and other special needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in social housing b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecause </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is allocated according to need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in many cases the home is purpose built or specifically adapt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s part of government policy over decades</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocial housing has been purpose built </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to cater for households with children - whose needs are not met by the open market - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and let to higher space standards. As a result there is a shortage of smaller propertie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n areas of low</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> homes are often purposely let under-occupied in order to achieve the most efficient use of public resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The DWP’s equality impact assessment estimated around two-thirds of those affected by the reform are disabled</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. As </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">part of our evidence gathering for this inquiry as to the impact of this reform CIH has interrogated the 2010/11 Family Resources Survey</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(FRS). Using this data we estimate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">households who did not have a spare room</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he remainder might reasonably be expected to move.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the time of writing our final figures are yet available, however, we do have some provisional estimates for the committee. The final results will be made available before it completes its inquiry. Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provisional estimates at this stage as follows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% (circa </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0,00</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> do not actually have a spare room</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of the remaining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">59</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0,000:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">25-35% (circa </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or their partner is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> severely disabled</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the remainder </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10-20% (circa </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or their partner is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; fon